💡 DETAILED ANALYSIS:
This document is highly effective for RAG because it is essentially a structured knowledge base. The semantic density is excellent—every line is a discrete fact (Software X is approved because Y; Software Z is disapproved because A). This makes it very easy for a vector database to perform high-precision retrieval when a user asks, "Is [Software Name] approved?"

The primary challenge is the tabular format spanning multiple pages. Standard PDF parsers often struggle to maintain the relationship between a software name on the left and its corresponding note on the right when the table breaks across pages. If the RAG pipeline splits a chunk in the middle of a table, the model might lose the connection between the software name and the security note. The content itself is clean and unambiguous, which is a major strength.

🔧 RECOMMENDED CHUNKING STRATEGY:
Hybrid Approach (Table-Aware Chunking).

Method: Do not use fixed-size character chunking. Use "Row-Based Chunking."
Strategy: Treat each row in the "Approved" and "Disapproved" tables as a single, atomic chunk.
Metadata Injection: For every row chunk, prepend the table header and the section title.
Example: "Section: Approved Software | Software Name: 1Password | Security Review Notes: This is the official and only supported password manager..."
Why: This ensures that even if a single row is retrieved, the LLM has the full context of what that row represents without needing to see the rest of the table.
